# Error Handling Refactor вҖ” Phase 3

## Preliminary Review of Prior Decisions

Before writing a single line of design, I need to audit what Phase 1 and Phase 2 established, because error handling touches both.

### From Phase 1 (Authentication)
- JWT signing: **RS256 only** вҖ” HS256 explicitly rejected (SEC-2025-041, CRITICAL)
- Auth errors must distinguish 401 (unauthenticated) from 403 (authenticated but unauthorized)
- Token validation via shared `@payments/auth-middleware` package
- JWKS endpoint at `/.well-known/jwks.json`

### From Phase 2 (Rate Limiting)
- Sliding window counter algorithm
- **429 responses MUST include `Retry-After` header** вҖ” contractual SLA obligation (CRITICAL)
- Also required: `X-RateLimit-Limit`, `X-RateLimit-Remaining`, `X-RateLimit-Reset`
- Redis fail-open behavior (rate limit failures should not block requests)

### From ADR-003 (Error Format)
- **All errors MUST use RFC 9457 Problem Details** (`application/problem+json`)
- Required fields: `type`, `title`, `status`, `detail`, `instance`
- Optional: `validation_errors`, `trace_id`, `retry_after`
- Error type registry at `https://api.payments.example/errors/`

---

## 1. Global Error Handling Strategy

### 1.1 Error Taxonomy

I'm defining a strict hierarchy so every error in the system maps to exactly one category. This prevents the common failure mode where different parts of the codebase produce inconsistent shapes.

```
AppError (base)
в”ңв”Җв”Җ AuthenticationError (401)     вҖ” no valid identity established
в”ңв”Җв”Җ AuthorizationError (403)      вҖ” identity established, access denied
в”ңв”Җв”Җ ValidationError (400)         вҖ” request shape/content invalid
в”ңв”Җв”Җ RateLimitError (429)          вҖ” too many requests
в”ңв”Җв”Җ NotFoundError (404)           вҖ” resource doesn't exist
в”ңв”Җв”Җ ConflictError (409)           вҖ” idempotency conflict, duplicate
в”ңв”Җв”Җ PaymentError (402)            вҖ” payment-specific failures
в”ңв”Җв”Җ GatewayError (502)            вҖ” upstream (Stripe) failure
в””в”Җв”Җ InternalError (500)           вҖ” unexpected server error
```

**Critical design decision**: `AuthenticationError` and `AuthorizationError` are separate classes, not a flag on a shared class. This makes it impossible to accidentally return a 403 when you mean 401 or vice versa вҖ” the type system enforces the distinction.

### 1.2 Base Error Class

```typescript
// src/errors/AppError.ts

import { randomUUID } from 'crypto';

/**
 * Base class for all application errors.
 * Every subclass MUST produce a valid RFC 9457 Problem Details response.
 * 
 * RFC 9457 required fields:
 *   type     вҖ” URI identifying the error type
 *   title    вҖ” short human-readable summary (stable, not occurrence-specific)
 *   status   вҖ” HTTP status code
 *   detail   вҖ” human-readable explanation for this specific occurrence
 *   instance вҖ” URI of the specific request that caused the error
 */
export abstract class AppError extends Error {
  abstract readonly type: string;
  abstract readonly title: string;
  abstract readonly status: number;

  readonly detail: string;
  readonly traceId: string;

  constructor(detail: string, traceId?: string) {
    super(detail);
    this.detail = detail;
    this.traceId = traceId ?? randomUUID();
    // Preserve prototype chain вҖ” required when extending Error in TypeScript
    Object.setPrototypeOf(this, new.target.prototype);
  }

  /**
   * Serialize to RFC 9457 Problem Details format.
   * The `instance` field is injected by the error handler (it knows the request path).
   * Subclasses override `extensions()` to add type-specific fields.
   */
  toProblРөРјDetails(instance: string): ProblemDetails {
    return {
      type: this.type,
      title: this.title,
      status: this.status,
      detail: this.detail,
      instance,
      trace_id: this.traceId,
      ...this.extensions(),
    };
  }

  /**
   * Subclasses override this to add extension fields.
   * Extension fields are merged into the Problem Details object.
   */
  protected extensions(): Record<string, unknown> {
    return {};
  }
}

export interface ProblemDetails {
  type: string;
  title: string;
  status: number;
  detail: string;
  instance: string;
  trace_id: string;
  [key: string]: unknown;
}
```

### 1.3 Concrete Error Classes

```typescript
// src/errors/AuthenticationError.ts

import { AppError } from './AppError';

/**
 * 401 Unauthorized вҖ” no valid identity could be established.
 * 
 * Use this when:
 * - No Authorization header present
 * - Token is malformed or unparseable
 * - Token signature is invalid
 * - Token is expired
 * - Token uses wrong algorithm (e.g., HS256 instead of RS256)
 * - Token issuer/audience mismatch
 * 
 * Do NOT use this for "user is authenticated but lacks permission" вҖ” that is
 * AuthorizationError (403). The distinction matters: 401 tells the client to
 * re-authenticate; 403 tells the client their credentials are fine but access
 * is denied regardless.
 */
export class AuthenticationError extends AppError {
  readonly type = 'https://api.payments.example/errors/authentication-required';
  readonly title = 'Authentication Required';
  readonly status = 401;

  constructor(detail: string, traceId?: string) {
    super(detail, traceId);
  }
}

// src/errors/AuthorizationError.ts

import { AppError } from './AppError';

/**
 * 403 Forbidden вҖ” identity is established, but access is denied.
 * 
 * Use this when:
 * - Token is valid and not expired
 * - User identity is confirmed
 * - BUT the user lacks the required permission or role
 * - OR the resource belongs to a different tenant
 * 
 * Do NOT use this when the token itself is invalid вҖ” that is
 * AuthenticationError (401).
 */
export class AuthorizationError extends AppError {
  readonly type = 'https://api.payments.example/errors/permission-denied';
  readonly title = 'Permission Denied';
  readonly status = 403;

  constructor(detail: string, traceId?: string) {
    super(detail, traceId);
  }
}

// src/errors/ValidationError.ts

import { AppError } from './AppError';

export interface FieldError {
  field: string;
  message: string;
  rejected_value?: unknown;
}

export class ValidationError extends AppError {
  readonly type = 'https://api.payments.example/errors/validation-failed';
  readonly title = 'Validation Failed';
  readonly status = 400;

  private readonly fieldErrors: FieldError[];

  constructor(detail: string, fieldErrors: FieldError[] = [], traceId?: string) {
    super(detail, traceId);
    this.fieldErrors = fieldErrors;
  }

  protected extensions() {
    return {
      validation_errors: this.fieldErrors,
    };
  }
}

// src/errors/RateLimitError.ts

import { AppError } from './AppError';

/**
 * 429 Too Many Requests.
 * 
 * IMPORTANT: This error carries rate limit metadata that MUST be reflected
 * in response headers. The error handler is responsible for reading
 * retryAfterSeconds and setting the Retry-After header.
 * 
 * The Retry-After header is a contractual SLA obligation per the partner
 * integration agreement (2025-Q3). It MUST be present on every 429 response.
 * See ADR-002 and the active HIGH constraint on rate-limiting scope.
 */
export class RateLimitError extends AppError {
  readonly type = 'https://api.payments.example/errors/rate-limited';
  readonly title = 'Rate Limit Exceeded';
  readonly status = 429;

  readonly retryAfterSeconds: number;
  readonly limitMax: number;
  readonly limitReset: number; // Unix timestamp

  constructor(
    detail: string,
    retryAfterSeconds: number,
    limitMax: number,
    limitReset: number,
    traceId?: string,
  ) {
    super(detail, traceId);
    this.retryAfterSeconds = retryAfterSeconds;
    this.limitMax = limitMax;
    this.limitReset = limitReset;
  }

  protected extensions() {
    return {
      retry_after: this.retryAfterSeconds,
    };
  }
}

// src/errors/PaymentError.ts

import { AppError } from './AppError';

export type PaymentErrorCode =
  | 'insufficient-funds'
  | 'card-declined'
  | 'invalid-payment-method'
  | 'idempotency-conflict';

const PAYMENT_ERROR_METADATA: Record<
  PaymentErrorCode,
  { type: string; title: string; status: number }
> = {
  'insufficient-funds': {
    type: 'https://api.payments.example/errors/insufficient-funds',
    title: 'Insufficient Funds',
    status: 402,
  },
  'card-declined': {
    type: 'https://api.payments.example/errors/card-declined',
    title: 'Card Declined',
    status: 402,
  },
  'invalid-payment-method': {
    type: 'https://api.payments.example/errors/invalid-payment-method',
    title: 'Invalid Payment Method',
    status: 400,
  },
  'idempotency-conflict': {
    type: 'https://api.payments.example/errors/idempotency-conflict',
    title: 'Idempotency Conflict',
    status: 409,
  },
};

export class PaymentError extends AppError {
  readonly type: string;
  readonly title: string;
  readonly status: number;

  constructor(code: PaymentErrorCode, detail: string, traceId?: string) {
    super(detail, traceId);
    const meta = PAYMENT_ERROR_METADATA[code];
    this.type = meta.type;
    this.title = meta.title;
    this.status = meta.status;
  }
}

// src/errors/GatewayError.ts

import { AppError } from './AppError';

/**
 * 502 Bad Gateway вҖ” upstream service (Stripe) returned an error.
 * 
 * IMPORTANT: Never include raw Stripe error messages in the `detail` field
 * in production. Stripe errors may contain internal details. Map them to
 * curated messages. See the error mapping table in the integration guide.
 */
export class GatewayError extends AppError {
  readonly type = 'https://api.payments.example/errors/gateway-error';
  readonly title = 'Payment Gateway Error';
  readonly status = 502;

  constructor(detail: string, traceId?: string) {
    super(detail, traceId);
  }
}

// src/errors/NotFoundError.ts

import { AppError } from './AppError';

export class NotFoundError extends AppError {
  readonly type = 'https://api.payments.example/errors/not-found';
  readonly title = 'Resource Not Found';
  readonly status = 404;

  constructor(detail: string, traceId?: string) {
    super(detail, traceId);
  }
}

// src/errors/InternalError.ts

import { AppError } from './AppError';

/**
 * 500 Internal Server Error вҖ” unexpected failure.
 * 
 * The detail field for InternalError should NEVER contain:
 * - Stack traces
 * - Database error messages
 * - Internal service names
 * - File paths
 * 
 * Log the full error internally; return only a safe generic message.
 * See SEC-2025-044.
 */
export class InternalError extends AppError {
  readonly type = 'https://api.payments.example/errors/internal-error';
  readonly title = 'Internal Server Error';
  readonly status = 500;

  constructor(traceId?: string) {
    // Detail is intentionally generic вҖ” never expose internals
    super(
      'An unexpected error occurred. Use the trace_id to reference this incident.',
      traceId,
    );
  }
}
```

### 1.4 Global Error Handler Middleware

This is the single most important piece. All errors funnel through here, ensuring consistent formatting regardless of where they originate.

```typescript
// src/middleware/errorHandler.ts

import { Request, Response, NextFunction } from 'express';
import { AppError, ProblemDetails } from '../errors/AppError';
import { RateLimitError } from '../errors/RateLimitError';
import { InternalError } from '../errors/InternalError';
import { logger } from '../lib/logger';

/**
 * Global error handling middleware.
 * 
 * MUST be registered LAST in the Express middleware chain.
 * Express identifies error handlers by their 4-argument signature (err, req, res, next).
 * 
 * Responsibilities:
 * 1. Normalize all errors to AppError subclasses
 * 2. Serialize to RFC 9457 Problem Details format
 * 3. Set correct Content-Type (application/problem+json)
 * 4. Set rate limit headers when error is RateLimitError
 * 5. Log appropriately (full detail internally, safe detail externally)
 * 6. Never leak internal details in 5xx responses
 */
export function globalErrorHandler(
  err: unknown,
  req: Request,
  res: Response,
  // next is required by Express even if unused вҖ” 4-arg signature identifies error handlers
  _next: NextFunction,
): void {
  const appError = normalizeError(err);
  const instance = req.path;

  // Log with appropriate severity
  // 5xx errors are unexpected вҖ” log at ERROR with full stack
  // 4xx errors are client errors вҖ” log at WARN with less detail
  if (appError.status >= 500) {
    logger.error({
      message: 'Unhandled server error',
      traceId: appError.traceId,
      error: err instanceof Error ? err.message : String(err),
      stack: err instanceof Error ? err.stack : undefined,
      path: req.path,
      method: req.method,
    });
  } else {
    logger.warn({
      message: 'Client error',
      traceId: appError.traceId,
      errorType: appError.type,
      status: appError.status,
      path: req.path,
      method: req.method,
    });
  }

  // Build the Problem Details response body
  const body: ProblemDetails = appError.toProblemDetails(instance);

  // Set headers before writing the response
  res.set('Content-Type', 'application/problem+json');

  // Rate limit errors require specific headers вҖ” contractual SLA obligation
  // Retry-After MUST be present on every 429 response (partner agreement 2025-Q3)
  if (appError instanceof RateLimitError) {
    res.set('Retry-After', String(appError.retryAfterSeconds));
    res.set('X-RateLimit-Limit', String(appError.limitMax));
    res.set('X-RateLimit-Remaining', '0');
    res.set('X-RateLimit-Reset', String(appError.limitReset));
  }

  // 401 responses should include WWW-Authenticate per RFC 9110
  if (appError.status === 401) {
    res.set('WWW-Authenticate', 'Bearer realm="payments-api"');
  }

  res.status(appError.status).json(body);
}

/**
 * Converts any thrown value into an AppError.
 * 
 * This is the safety net: if something throws a raw Error, a string,
 * or any non-AppError value, we wrap it in InternalError so the response
 * is always RFC 9457 compliant
